(14, 'use-of-icetabs-for-efficient-examination-and-clearance-process---reg', 'Use of ICETABs for efficient examination and clearance process - reg. ', 'The Customs Act, 1962', 'Circular / Notification', 'Circular No. 10/2024-Customs', 'Circular No. 10/2024-Customs,  Use of ICETABs for efficient examination and clearance process - reg', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\">F.No.450/128/2024-Cus IV<br>Government of India<br>Ministry of Finance, Department of Revenue<br>(Central Board of Indirect Taxes &amp; Customs)</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Circular No. 10/2024-Customs</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Subject: Use of ICETABs for efficient examination and clearance process.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Sustained efforts by CBIC in simplifying trade procedures, enhancing transparency, and adopting best practices have enabled it to achieve steady improvements across various trade facilitation&nbsp;indicators, as reflected in the Global Survey on Digital and Sustainable Trade Facilitation conducted&nbsp;by the UNESCAP 2023. As per the Global Report 2023, India&rsquo;s overall trade facilitation&nbsp;implementation score has improved from 78.49 per cent in 2019 to 93.55 per cent in 2023. CBIC has&nbsp;also released a Customs Ease of Doing Business Compendium 2024 which details recent trade&nbsp;facilitation initiatives of CBIC. Copy of compendium is available at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cbic.gov.in/entities/cbic-content-mst/NTE2\">https://www.cbic.gov.in/entities/cbic-content-mst/NTE2</a>.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">In view of the objective of trade facilitation, transparency and efficiency in Customs processes,&nbsp;CBIC has decided use of ICETAB for speedy examination of import consignments. In brief, ICETAB&nbsp;is a mobile tablet device for use by Customs Officers for facilitating quick upload of the examination&nbsp;report on the go in real time basis and making the examination process transparent and faster. ICETAB&nbsp;contains an exclusive Mobile Application to enable examining officers to,-<br>(a) view RMS Instructions, Examination Order and Bill of Entry (BE) details along with&nbsp;other supporting documents;<br>(b) capture upto four images of cargo examination for integration with the Bill of Entry<br>(c) submit examination report immediately on completion of the cargo examination thus&nbsp;reducing the time taken in examination process and making the process seamless and&nbsp;paperless.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Customs cargo clearance is based on Risk Management System where on the basis of risk&nbsp;associated, few consignments are intervened for assessment and examination. After assessment&nbsp;procedure is complete, the assessed copy of Bill of Entry is electronically made available to importer/&nbsp;Customs Broker for duty payment and prepare the cargo ready for examination by Customs officer. In&nbsp;absence of holistic mobility coverage, Examining officers were relying on printed copy of assessed BE&nbsp;for examination as it contains Examination Order and other instructions. With this launch of new&nbsp;version of ICETAB from 23.08.2024, the examination order will be seamlessly available to Examining&nbsp;officer on ICETAB. Accordingly, there will be no requirement for any paper documents for the purpose&nbsp;of carrying out examination.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">Examining officer, on the basis of instructions already made available through ICETAB, will&nbsp;have to take and upload four images of the cargo being examined. The images should cover key aspects&nbsp;of examination. These images will also be integrated in e-Sanchit repository for subsequent viewing.&nbsp;The examining officers should also upload the examination report immediately using the ICETAB.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">A detailed advisory for the use of ICETABs will be issued by DG Systems. In cases of&nbsp;exigencies where the report cannot be given using ICETAB, prior permission of concerned Assistant&nbsp;Commissioner is required and same may be recorded in the examination report as well. The Pr.&nbsp;Commissioner of Customs/ Commissioner of Customs having jurisdiction over the import shed, on&nbsp;weekly basis, review the use of ICETABs and resolve any technical difficulty immediately in&nbsp;consultation with DG Systems. The Commissioner of Customs shall ensure network connectivity for&nbsp;efficient functioning of ICETABs.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">This Circular may be given wide publicity by issue of suitable Trade Notice/Public Notice. All&nbsp;Stakeholders under your jurisdiction may be instructed suitably and officers may also be sensitized of these changes. Any difficulty faced by stakeholders may be brought to notice of the Board.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>', 32, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-08-21 06:14:43'),
(15, 'composite-supply-and-mixed-supply', 'Composite Supply and Mixed Supply', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Section 8', 'Section 8, Composite Supply, Mixed Supply, Tax Treatment, Composite Supply Example, Mixed Supply Example,', '../../asset/uploads/Mixed Supply.jpg', '<p><strong>Section 8 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017</strong> deals with the taxation of \"composite\" and \"mixed\" supplies under the GST regime in India. This section is important because it determines how different combinations of goods and/or services are taxed when supplied together. Here\'s a breakdown:</p>\r\n<h3>1. <strong>Composite Supply</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Definition</strong>: A composite supply consists of two or more goods or services that are naturally bundled and supplied together in the ordinary course of business, where one of the supplies is a principal supply.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Tax Treatment</strong>: The tax rate applicable to a composite supply is the rate applicable to the principal supply. For example, if a package includes transportation (service) and insurance (service), where transportation is the principal supply, the entire supply is taxed at the rate applicable to transportation services.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>2. <strong>Mixed Supply</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Definition</strong>: A mixed supply consists of two or more individual goods or services made together for a single price, but which do not constitute a composite supply. In other words, the supplies are not naturally bundled and can be sold separately.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Tax Treatment</strong>: The tax rate for a mixed supply is determined by the highest rate applicable to any of the goods or services in that supply. For instance, a gift hamper containing items like chocolates, cosmetics, and stationery (each with different GST rates) will be taxed at the highest rate applicable to any of those items.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Key Points Under Section 8:</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The tax treatment of supplies under Section 8 ensures there is clarity on how bundled goods and services are taxed.</li>\r\n<li>This section aims to prevent any manipulation or avoidance of tax by supplying goods or services in combinations that might otherwise lead to a lower tax rate.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Illustrations:</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Composite Supply Example</strong>: A travel package including airfare, accommodation, and meals where the airfare is the principal supply.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Mixed Supply Example</strong>: A festival combo pack containing sweets, candles, and decorative items sold for a single price, where each item could be sold separately.</li>\r\n</ul>', 6, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:21:31'),
(16, 'time-of-supply-of-goods-under-the-gst', 'Time of supply of goods under the GST', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Section 12', 'Section 12, Section 12 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017 specifies the rules for determining the \"time of supply\" of goods under the GST regime in India. The \"time of supply\" is crucial because it dictates when a transaction is consid', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p><strong>Section 12 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017</strong> specifies the rules for determining the \"time of supply\" of goods under the GST regime in India. The \"time of supply\" is crucial because it dictates when a transaction is considered to have occurred for GST purposes, thereby determining the point in time when GST liability arises.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Key Provisions of Section 12: Time of Supply of Goods</strong></h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>General Rule (Section 12(2))</strong>: The time of supply of goods is the earliest of the following dates:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Date of issue of the invoice</strong> by the supplier; or</li>\r\n<li><strong>Last date on which the invoice should have been issued</strong> under Section 31 (which generally mandates the issuance of an invoice within a specified time frame after the supply); or</li>\r\n<li><strong>Date of receipt of payment</strong> (to the extent the payment is received).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: The \"date of receipt of payment\" is the earlier of the date when the payment is entered in the books of accounts of the supplier or the date on which the payment is credited to the supplier\'s bank account.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Special Cases for Time of Supply of Goods:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Goods on Approval Basis (Section 12(2)(c))</strong>: If goods are sent on approval or sale or return basis, the time of supply shall be the earlier of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The date when the buyer confirms the acceptance; or</li>\r\n<li>6 months from the date of removal of goods.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Continuous Supply of Goods (Section 12(2)(b))</strong>: For continuous supply of goods, where successive statements of accounts or payments are involved, the time of supply is the earliest of the dates mentioned in those statements.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Special Cases (Section 12(3))</strong>: In cases where the supply involves an addition in the value by way of interest, late fees, or penalty for delayed payment, the time of supply shall be the date on which the supplier receives such additional consideration.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><strong>Example to Illustrate Section 12:</strong></h3>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 1: General Rule</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A supplier sells goods to a customer on June 1, 2024. The supplier issues the invoice on June 5, 2024, but the customer pays on June 3, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Date of Invoice: June 5, 2024.</li>\r\n<li>Last Date on which the invoice should have been issued: June 1, 2024 (assuming it should be issued on or before the date of delivery under the applicable rules).</li>\r\n<li>Date of receipt of payment: June 3, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Result</strong>: The time of supply will be the earliest of these dates, which is <strong>June 1, 2024</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 2: Goods Sent on Approval Basis</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A seller sends goods on a sale or return basis to a buyer on April 1, 2024. The buyer confirms acceptance of the goods on July 1, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Date of buyer\'s acceptance: July 1, 2024.</li>\r\n<li>Six months from the date of removal (April 1, 2024 + 6 months) = October 1, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Result</strong>: The time of supply will be the earliest of these dates, which is <strong>July 1, 2024</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 3: Continuous Supply of Goods</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A supplier enters into a contract to supply goods over a period of 6 months, with invoices raised monthly based on the goods supplied each month.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The time of supply will be the earliest of the dates mentioned in the successive invoices or the date of receipt of payment, whichever is earlier, for each month&rsquo;s supply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', 1, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:25:03'),
(17, 'time-of-supply-of-services-under-the-gst', 'Time of supply of services under the GST', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Section 13', 'Section 13 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017 specifies the rules for determining the \"time of supply\" of services under the GST regime in India. The \"time of supply\" determines when a transaction is considered to have occurred for GST', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p><strong>Section 13 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017</strong> specifies the rules for determining the \"time of supply\" of services under the GST regime in India. The \"time of supply\" determines when a transaction is considered to have occurred for GST purposes, which in turn dictates when GST liability arises for services.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Key Provisions of Section 13: Time of Supply of Services</strong></h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>General Rule (Section 13(2))</strong>: The time of supply of services shall be the earliest of the following dates:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Date of issue of the invoice</strong> by the supplier, if the invoice is issued within the prescribed period (30 days from the date of supply of service, or 45 days in certain cases); or</li>\r\n<li><strong>Date of receipt of payment</strong> (to the extent of payment received), whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n<li>If the invoice is not issued within the prescribed period, the time of supply shall be the <strong>date of provision of service</strong> or the <strong>date of receipt of payment</strong>, whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: The \"date of receipt of payment\" is the earlier of:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The date on which the payment is entered in the books of accounts of the supplier; or</li>\r\n<li>The date on which the payment is credited to the supplier\'s bank account.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Time of Supply in Case of Reverse Charge (Section 13(3))</strong>: For services liable to GST under the reverse charge mechanism, the time of supply shall be the earliest of the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Date of payment</strong> as entered in the books of accounts of the recipient or the date on which the payment is debited from the recipient\'s bank account, whichever is earlier; or</li>\r\n<li><strong>31st day from the date of issue of the invoice</strong> or any other document by the supplier.</li>\r\n<li>If none of the above applies, the time of supply shall be the date of entry in the books of accounts of the recipient of supply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Special Cases (Section 13(4), 13(5), and 13(6))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Addition in Value by Way of Interest, Late Fee, or Penalty (Section 13(6))</strong>: If there is any addition to the value of supply by way of interest, late fee, or penalty for delayed payment, the time of supply shall be the date on which the supplier receives such additional consideration.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Continuous Supply of Services (Section 13(5))</strong>: For continuous supply of services where:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The due date of payment is ascertainable from the contract, the time of supply is the date on which the payment is due.</li>\r\n<li>The due date of payment is not ascertainable from the contract, the time of supply is the date of receipt of payment.</li>\r\n<li>The payment is linked to the completion of an event, the time of supply is the date of completion of that event.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Supply Ceases Before Completion (Section 13(7))</strong>: In cases where there is a cessation of supply of services before its completion, the time of supply shall be the date on which the supply ceases.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><strong>Examples to Illustrate Section 13:</strong></h3>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 1: General Rule</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A consulting firm provides services on July 1, 2024, and issues the invoice on July 10, 2024. The payment is received on July 5, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Date of Invoice: July 10, 2024 (issued within the prescribed period).</li>\r\n<li>Date of Payment Receipt: July 5, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Result</strong>: The time of supply is the earliest of these dates, which is <strong>July 5, 2024</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 2: Reverse Charge Mechanism</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A business receives legal services from an advocate on July 1, 2024, and receives an invoice on July 5, 2024. The payment is made on August 1, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Date of Payment: August 1, 2024.</li>\r\n<li>31st day from the invoice date: August 5, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Result</strong>: The time of supply is the earliest of these dates, which is <strong>August 1, 2024</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 3: Continuous Supply of Services</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A software company enters into a contract to provide monthly maintenance services for 12 months, and the contract specifies that payments are due on the 5th of each month.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Due date of payment for the month of July: July 5, 2024.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Result</strong>: The time of supply for the service provided in July will be <strong>July 5, 2024</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', 5, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:29:51'),
(18, 'section-31-of-the-central-goods-and-services-tax-cgst-act', 'Section 31 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Section 31', 'Section 31 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017 provides the rules regarding the issuance of tax invoices, credit notes, and debit notes under the GST regime in India. This section is critical for ensuring proper documentation, which is', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p><strong>Section 31 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017</strong> provides the rules regarding the issuance of tax invoices, credit notes, and debit notes under the GST regime in India. This section is critical for ensuring proper documentation, which is essential for claiming input tax credits, filing GST returns, and maintaining compliance with GST laws.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Key Provisions of Section 31: Issuance of Tax Invoice, Credit, and Debit Notes</strong></h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Issuance of Tax Invoice for Supply of Goods (Section 31(1))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A registered person supplying taxable goods must issue a tax invoice <strong>before or at the time of removal of goods</strong> for supply to the recipient, where the supply involves the movement of goods; or</li>\r\n<li>In other cases, <strong>before or at the time of delivery</strong> of goods or making them available to the recipient.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Issuance of Tax Invoice for Supply of Services (Section 31(2))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A registered person supplying taxable services must issue a tax invoice <strong>before or after the provision of the service</strong> but within a prescribed period, which is generally <strong>30 days</strong> from the date of supply of services (45 days in case of insurance companies, banking companies, financial institutions, and non-banking financial companies).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Manner of Issuance (Section 31(3))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A tax invoice shall contain specific details as prescribed (such as the name, address, and GSTIN of the supplier and recipient, description of goods or services, quantity, value, tax charged, etc.).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Receipt Voucher or Other Document (Section 31(3)(d))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A registered person must issue a <strong>receipt voucher or any other document</strong> if they receive advance payment for any goods or services.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Refund Voucher (Section 31(3)(e))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In cases where a receipt voucher has been issued but no supply has been made, a <strong>refund voucher</strong> must be issued to the person who made the advance payment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Issuance of Credit Notes and Debit Notes (Section 31(3)(c) and 31(3)(f))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A <strong>credit note</strong> can be issued by a supplier to the recipient in the following cases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Taxable value or tax charged in the invoice exceeds the actual taxable value or tax payable.</li>\r\n<li>Goods supplied are returned, or services are found to be deficient.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>A <strong>debit note</strong> can be issued by a supplier to the recipient in the following cases:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Taxable value or tax charged in the invoice is less than the actual taxable value or tax payable.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Bill of Supply (Section 31(3)(b))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A <strong>bill of supply</strong> is required instead of a tax invoice when a registered person is supplying exempted goods or services or when they have opted to pay tax under the composition scheme.</li>\r\n<li>A bill of supply does not include details of tax charged, as no tax is charged on exempted supplies or supplies under the composition scheme.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Revised Tax Invoices (Section 31(3)(a))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A registered person may issue a <strong>revised tax invoice</strong> in respect of any taxable supply made between the effective date of registration and the date of issuance of the registration certificate.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p><strong>Special Cases of Invoicing (Section 31(4) and 31(5))</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For continuous supply of goods or services, where successive statements of accounts or successive payments are involved, the invoice must be issued <strong>before or at the time of such statements or payment</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>In cases of goods sent on approval for sale, the invoice must be issued <strong>before or at the time of supply</strong> or within 6 months from the date of removal, whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h3><strong>Examples to Illustrate Section 31:</strong></h3>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 1: Issuance of Tax Invoice for Goods</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A manufacturer sells goods to a retailer and moves the goods from the factory to the retailer&rsquo;s location on July 1, 2024. The invoice must be issued <strong>before or at the time of removal of goods</strong>, which means the invoice should be issued on or before July 1, 2024.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 2: Issuance of Tax Invoice for Services</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A consulting firm provides services to a client on July 15, 2024. The tax invoice must be issued <strong>within 30 days</strong> from the date of supply of service, i.e., by August 14, 2024.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 3: Issuance of Credit Note</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A supplier issues an invoice to a customer for goods worth ₹50,000, but later realizes that the actual value of the goods should have been ₹40,000. The supplier can issue a <strong>credit note</strong> to the customer for the excess amount charged (₹10,000).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 4: Bill of Supply</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A small retailer who has opted for the composition scheme supplies exempt goods. The retailer must issue a <strong>bill of supply</strong> instead of a tax invoice for these goods.</li>\r\n</ul>', 6, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:38:10'),
(19, 'time-of-supply-when-there-is-a-change-in-the-gst-rate-for-goods-or-services', 'Time of supply when there is a change in the GST rate for goods or services', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Section 14', 'Section 14 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017 deals with the determination of the \"time of supply\" when there is a change in the GST rate for goods or services. This section provides clarity on how to determine the time of supply—and t', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p><strong>Section 14 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Act, 2017</strong> deals with the determination of the \"time of supply\" when there is a change in the GST rate for goods or services. This section provides clarity on how to determine the time of supply&mdash;and therefore the applicable GST rate&mdash;when the tax rate changes between the date of supply and the issuance of the invoice or receipt of payment.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Key Provisions of Section 14: Change in Rate of Tax in Respect of Supply of Goods or Services</strong></h3>\r\n<p>When there is a change in the rate of tax, Section 14 provides different scenarios to determine the \"time of supply\" based on the timing of the issuance of the invoice and the receipt of payment. The section is divided into two main parts: one for goods and the other for services.</p>\r\n<h4><strong>1. Change in Rate of Tax: Supply of Goods or Services</strong></h4>\r\n<p>There are three main scenarios covered under Section 14:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Scenario 1: Supply Made Before Change in Tax Rate</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>If the supply of goods or services is made before the change in the tax rate,</strong> and:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Invoice is issued and payment is received after the change:</strong> The time of supply will be the date of the issue of the invoice or the date of receipt of payment, whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Scenario 2: Supply Made After Change in Tax Rate</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>If the supply of goods or services is made after the change in the tax rate,</strong> and:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Invoice is issued and payment is received before the change:</strong> The time of supply will be the date of issue of the invoice or the date of receipt of payment, whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Scenario 3: Part of the Transaction Occurs Before and After Change in Tax Rate</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>If the invoice is issued before the change, but the payment is received after the change, or vice versa:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The time of supply will be determined by either the date of receipt of payment or the date of the issuance of the invoice, whichever is earlier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>Illustrative Examples for Section 14</strong></h3>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 1: Supply Before Change in Rate</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A supplier provides goods to a customer on August 1, 2024, before a GST rate increase from 12% to 18% on August 10, 2024. The invoice is issued, and the payment is received on August 15, 2024, after the rate change.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Analysis</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supply before the rate change.</li>\r\n<li>Invoice issued and payment received after the rate change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>: The time of supply will be the earlier of the date of the issue of the invoice (August 15, 2024) or the date of receipt of payment (August 15, 2024). Since both occur after the change, the new rate of 18% will apply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 2: Supply After Change in Rate</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A service provider renders a service on August 15, 2024, after the GST rate change from 18% to 12% on August 10, 2024. The invoice is issued, and the payment is received on August 1, 2024, before the rate change.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Analysis</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Supply after the rate change.</li>\r\n<li>Invoice issued and payment received before the rate change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>: The time of supply will be the earlier of the date of issue of the invoice (August 1, 2024) or the date of receipt of payment (August 1, 2024). Since both occur before the change, the old rate of 18% will apply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Example 3: Transaction Spanning Rate Change</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A supplier provides goods on August 5, 2024. The GST rate changes from 5% to 12% on August 10, 2024. The invoice is issued on August 1, 2024 (before the change), but the payment is received on August 15, 2024 (after the change).\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Analysis</strong>:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Invoice issued before the rate change.</li>\r\n<li>Payment received after the rate change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Time of Supply</strong>: The time of supply will be determined by the earlier of the date of issue of the invoice (August 1, 2024) or the date of receipt of payment (August 15, 2024). Here, the earlier date is <strong>August 1, 2024</strong>. Since it is before the change, the old rate of 5% will apply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', 11, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:41:13'),
(20, 'value-of-supply-of-goods-or-services-where-the-consideration-is-not-wholly-in-money', 'Value of Supply of Goods or Services Where the Consideration is Not Wholly in Money', 'The GST Act, 2017', 'Act', 'Rule 27', 'Rule 27 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Rules, 2017 deals with the method for determining the value of supply of goods or services when the consideration is not wholly in money. This rule is particularly relevant in cases where a transaction ', '../../asset/vectors/DefaultBlogImage.svg', '<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Rule 27 of the Central Goods and Services Tax (CGST) Rules, 2017</strong> deals with the method for determining the value of supply of goods or services when the consideration is not wholly in money. This rule is particularly relevant in cases where a transaction involves a part-monetary and part-non-monetary exchange (such as bartering or exchanging goods/services).</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Key Provisions of Rule 27: Value of Supply of Goods or Services Where the Consideration is Not Wholly in Money</strong></h3>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rule 27 outlines the method to determine the value of the supply of goods or services when the consideration received is not entirely in money. The value of supply shall be determined by following these methods in order of preference:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<p><strong>Open Market Value (OMV)</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The value of the supply shall be the <strong>open market value</strong> of such supply.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Open Market Value</strong> is defined as the full value in money, excluding the GST, payable by a person in an open market where the supplier and the recipient are not related, and the price is the sole consideration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<p><strong>Sum of Consideration in Money + Money Equivalent of Consideration Not in Money</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>If the open market value is not available, the value of supply shall be the sum total of:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The <strong>consideration in money</strong>; and</li>\r\n<li>Any such further amount in money equivalent to the consideration not in money, if such amount is known at the time of supply.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Value of Supply of Goods or Services of Like Kind and Quality</strong>:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">If the value cannot be determined under the first two methods, the value of supply shall be the value of supply of goods or services of <strong>like kind and quality</strong>.</li>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: justify;\">\"Goods or services of like kind and quality\" means goods or services which are similar in nature, characteristics, quality, and functionality.\r\n<h3 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Examples to Illustrate Rule 27:</strong></h3>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Example 1: Open Market Value</strong></h4>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A dealer supplies a refrigerator (goods) worth ₹30,000 to a customer, who in turn provides services worth ₹10,000 to the dealer as partial payment. The open market value of the refrigerator is ₹30,000.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Value of Supply</strong>: The value of supply of the refrigerator is the <strong>open market value</strong> of ₹30,000 since it is available.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Example 2: Sum of Consideration in Money and Equivalent Value in Money</strong></h4>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A jeweler supplies a gold necklace to a customer in exchange for an old gold necklace plus ₹15,000 in cash. The value of the old necklace is known to be ₹25,000.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Value of Supply</strong>: The value of supply will be the sum total of the consideration in money (₹15,000) and the money equivalent of the old necklace (₹25,000), which is <strong>₹40,000</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong>Example 3: Goods or Services of Like Kind and Quality</strong></h4>\r\n<ul style=\"text-align: justify;\">\r\n<li><strong>Scenario</strong>: A car dealer provides a car in exchange for an older car, plus ₹2,00,000 in cash. If the open market value of the new car is not available, but a similar car (same model and features) is sold by the dealer for ₹8,00,000.\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Value of Supply</strong>: The value of supply will be the value of the car of <strong>like kind and quality</strong>, which is <strong>₹8,00,000</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', 6, 'C. A. Manish Suvasiya', '2024-09-03 09:46:00');

